               <p>JAMES CRIPPS. I <rs id="t18250915-281-viclabel1508" type="occupation">keep a cook's-shop</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18250915-281-victim1405 t18250915-281-viclabel1508"></join>, in <placeName id="t18250915-281-crimeloc1509">Chapel-street, Mary-le-bone</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18250915-281-crimeloc1509" type="placeName" value="Chapel-street, Mary-le-bone"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18250915-281-crimeloc1509" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18250915-281-off1506 t18250915-281-crimeloc1509"></join>. On the 15th of July I heard a noise in my shop, and saw the prisoner by the side of the counter - he asked for some pease-pudding - I said I had none, and on going round the counter I saw my till was out, and the money taken from it, some of which had been in a tin-box, and some loose in the till - I had seen it about a quarter of an hour before, and no other person had been in the shop; I then looked on the counter, and saw the tin box, and the prisoner's hand under the scale on the counter. I said, "You have got my money;" the money I had in the till was two half-crowns, a shilling, and a sixpence; he said, "I have 6 s. 6 d. of my own." The whole of the money in the till and box was five half-crowns, some silver, and some copper.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18250915-281-person1406">
                  J 
                  - WILLS
               <interp inst="t18250915-281-person1406" type="surname" value="- WILLS"></interp>
